w.idlebrain.com/celeb/starhomes/venky/boxoffice.html</ref> and Rs.26.3 million in its opening week.<ref name=\"idlebrain.com\"/>\nIt was the third highest grossing Telugu film of all time, at its release.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe film had a 50-day run in 93 centres<ref>[http://idlebrain.com/trade/tsynop/tradestory24.html Cycle Stand - Telugu Cinema Trade Story<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and a 100-day run in 57 centres.<ref>[http://idlebrain.com/trade/tsynop/tradestory32.html Cycle Stand - Telugu Cinema Trade Story<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It had a 175-day run in three centres.<ref>[http://www.cinegoer.com/venky175.htm CineGoer.com - Box-Office Records And Collections - Venkatesh's 175-Day Centres List<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212224008/http://www.cinegoer.com/venky175.htm |date=12 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0311594|title=Nuvvu Naaku Nachav}}\n\n\n{{Nandi Award for Best Home Viewing Feature Film}}\n{{K. Vijaya Bhaskar}}\n{{Trivikram Srinivas}}\n\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Films set in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Koti]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: telugu \u2192 Telugu, highest grossing \u2192 highest-grossing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuvvu_Naaku_Nachav"}
{"title_page": "Direct-to-home television in India", "text_new": "[[Direct-to-home|Direct-to-Home]] (DTH) television is a method of receiving [[satellite television]] by means of signals transmitted from [[direct-broadcast satellite]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pattan|first=Bruno|date=31 March 1993|title=Satellite Systems:Principles and Technologies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0GJWEro9ea4C&dq=sun+outage+satellite&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location=Berlin|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|page=|isbn=9780442013578|access-date=29 July 2014}}</ref> The Government of India permitted the reception and distribution of satellite television signals in November 2000. The first DTH service in the country was launched by [[Dish TV]] on 2 October 2003. [[DD Free Dish]], the first free DTH service in India, was launched by public broadcaster [[Doordarshan|Prasar Bharati]] in December 2004.\n\nIndia is the largest DTH market in the world by number of subscribers. As on 30 June 2019, there were 54.36&nbsp;million active pay DTH subscribers in the country.<ref name=\"TRAIpir\">{{cite press release | url=https://main.trai.gov.in/sites/default/files/PIR_01102019_0.pdf | title=The Indian Telecom Services Performance Indicators | publisher=TRAI | date=1 October 2019 | accessdate=4 October 2019 | page=94-95}}</ref> These figures do not include subscribers of free DTH services. \n\nThe Indian market is serviced by 4 paid DTH providers and one free DTH provider as of Sept 2019.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background ===\nDTH services were first proposed in India in 1996. The proposal was not approved to due to concerns over national security and negative cultural influence. In 1997, the [[Government of India]] banned DTH services when [[Rupert Murdoch]]-owned Indian Sky Broadcasting (ISkyB) was about to launch its DTH services in the country.<ref name=\"Rediff1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2004/mar/23spec.htm|title=What is DTH?|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> After deliberations among groups of ministers, DTH services were permitted by the [[Third Vajpayee ministry|NDA government]] in November 2000. The ministers made four key recommendations to govern DTH services: no single entity, either private or state-owned, should be permitted a [[monopoly]] in DTH services; the [[vertical integration]] of DTH and [[cable television]] services should be monitored in order to prevent the formation of a monopoly in television distribution; the vertical integration of DTH operators and television channels should be avoided in order to ensure fair competition among TV channels.\n\nThe new policy announced in November 2000 required all DTH operators to set up earth stations in India within 12 months of receiving a license. DTH licenses were priced at $2.14 million with a validity of 10 years. The FDI limit in the DTH sector was capped at 49%, and the company operating the services was required to be headed by an Indian citizen.<ref name=\"Rediff1\"/>\n\n=== Early years ===\nThe first DTH service was launched in India on 2 October 2003 by [[Dish TV]] owned by [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises|Zee]]. The company decided not to compete against entrenched cable operators in metros and urban areas, and instead focused on providing services to rural areas and regions not serviced by cable television. Dish TV acquired 350,000 subscribers within 2 years of the launch.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/10-years-of-dth-in-india-the-other-electronics-revolution-114010100022_1.html|title=10 years of DTH in India: The other electronics revolution|last=Gupta|first=Surajeet Das|date=2014-01-01|newspaper=Business Standard India|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> Public broadcaster [[Doordarshan|Prasar Bharati]] launched DD Direct Plus (now [[DD Free Dish]]) in December 2004. The service is free and offers only [[free-to-air]] channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-prasar-bharati-dth-moving-to-pay-mode-1277779|title=Prasar Bharati DTH moving to pay mode? {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=2009-07-28|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> [[Tata Sky]] was incorporated in 2004 as joint venture between the [[Tata Group]] and [[21st Century Fox|Star India's Parent Company]]. Tata Sky launched DTH services in August 2006. Unlike Dish TV, Tata Sky focused on metros and large cities hoping to attract customers away from cable by offering better picture and audio quality and wider selection of channels.<ref name=\":1\" /> Following legal proceedings between [[Star TV (Asian TV networks)|STAR]] and Zee, in 2007, the two companies called a truce and began offering their channels on each other's services. This decision and Dish TV's acquisition of more transponders enabled them to offer 150 channels on their service, more than any other DTH service in India at the time.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSun Direct and Airtel digital TV launched services in 2007 and 2008 respectively. Reliance Big TV (now [[Reliance Digital TV|Independent TV]]) was launched in August 2008.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/money/2009/apr/29big-tv-to-divest-in-dth-arm.htm \"Big TV launched in August 2008\"]. Retrieved 14 April 2010.</ref> The service acquired 1 million subscribers within 90 days of launch, the fastest ramp-up ever achieved by any DTH operator in the world.<ref>[http://www.powerhomebiz.com/News/112008/big-tv-india2.htm \"BIG TV crosses 1 Million Subscriber Mark Within The 90 Days of Launch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429061849/http://www.powerhomebiz.com/News/112008/big-tv-india2.htm |date=2014-04-29 }}. Retrieved 14 April 2010.</ref> [[Videocon d2h]] launched its services in June 2009.\n\nThe total number of DTH subscribers in India rose from 1.5 million in 2005 to 23 million in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/management/kit-the-dth-industry-in-india-110112200007_1.html|title=KIT: The DTH industry in India|last=Advisors|first=Technopak|date=2010-11-22|newspaper=Business Standard India|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> Sun Direct became the first DTH provider to offer [[High-definition television|high-definition]] (HD) channels in early 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/26440_Discovery-launches-Indias-first-high-definition-channel|title=Discovery launches India's first high definition channel|website=www.afaqs.com|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> Tata Sky began offering HD channels later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/56702/tata-sky-launch-hdtv-more.html|title=Tata Sky to launch HDTV, more interactive channels this year|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> Other DTH providers subsequently began carrying HD channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesstoday.in/gadget/living-tech/hd-channels-a-question-of-resolution/story/18596.html|title=HD Channels: A Question of Resolution|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\n====A la carte====\n{{further information|A la carte pay television}}\nOn 3 September 2007, the [[Telecom Regulatory Authority of India]] (TRAI) issued the ''Telecommunication (Broadcasting and Cable Services) Interconnection (Fourth Amendment) Regulation 2007'', which went into law on December 1; the rules require all broadcasters to offer channels on an [[A la carte pay television|a la carte]] basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/sep/sep28.php|title=Broadcasters to give channels a la carte to DTH operators: Trai|date=September 3, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/09/04/stories/2007090461131300.htm|title=Broadcasters must offer all channels|date=September 4, 2007|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> The regulation states, \"All broadcasters will compulsorily offer all their channels on a la carte basis to DTH operators. Additionally, they may also offer bouquets, but they will not compel any DTH operator to include the entire bouquet in any package being offered by DTH operators to their subscribers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200709031641.htm|title=DTH companies can pick channels of choice: TRAI|date=September 3, 2007|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=May 12, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629104908/http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200709031641.htm|archive-date=June 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Prior to the regulation, only customers in areas covered by the [[conditional access]] system (CAS), and cable systems providing the services, had the option of choosing to buy only the channels they were interested in. TRAI intervened after DTH operators complained that broadcasters were forcing them to carry channels that they did not want.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/6kzrHbFbry3ztsQ5uhVaeK/Trai-unbundles-TV-channels-for-DTH.html|title=Trai unbundles TV channels for DTH|author=Sreejiraj Eluvangal|date=September 4, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=Livemint}}</ref>\n\nSeveral broadcasters, such as [[STAR India]], [[Zee Turner Limited|Zee Turner]], [[Sony Entertainment Television (India)|Set Discovery]] and [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]], challenged TRAI's order in the [[Telecom Disputes Settlement Appellate Tribunal]] (TDSAT).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/nov/nov231.php|title=Zee joins Sony to challenge Trai's regulation in non-CAS areas|date=November 21, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k8/jan/jan32.php|title=Sun moves Tdsat against Trai's a la carte pricing for non-CAS areas|date=January 4, 2008|website=IndianTelevision.com|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/nov/nov246.php|title=A la carte Tariff Order valid from 1 Dec, Tdsat refuses stay|date=November 22, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref> On 15 January 2008, TDSAT refused to grant a stay on the appeal challenging TRAI's directive; TDSAT overruled the broadcasters' objections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/tdsat-refuses-stay-on-trai-directive-to-broadcasters/261771|title=TDSAT refuses stay on Trai directive to broadcasters|date=January 15, 2008|website=Financial Express|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> The agency later set aside TRAI's December 2007 tariff regime. TRAI challenged TDSAT's order in the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]], and stated in proceedings on 22 July 2010 that \"in the [[Analog television|analog]], [[Cable converter box#Addressable cable box|non-addressable]] environment, the authority is of the view that a la carte should not be made mandatory at the wholesale level as technological constraints in any case make it impossible for the benefits of a la carte provisioning to be passed on to subscribers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-07-22/news/27594209_1_la-carte-telecom-regulatory-authority-trai|title=Trai wants to cap cable rate at Rs 250/month|author=Sanjay K Singh|date=July 22, 2010|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=India Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/trai-seeks-sc-nod-to-notify-tariff-order/742347/|title=TRAI seeks SC nod to notify tariff order|date=January 26, 2011|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTRAI ordered that pay television customers in India must be given a free choice of channels rather than be forced to choose package deals, enforcing a January 2011 deadline to implement the changes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/article528738.ece|title=A la carte menu for DTH subscribers at Rs. 150|date=July 22, 2010|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-07-23/news/27614290_1_tariff-order-dth-providers-broadcasters|title=Pick and pay DTH channels from September|date=July 23, 2010|newspaper=India Times|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> The order stated, \"Every service provider providing broadcasting services or cable services to its subscribers using an [[Addressability|addressable system]] shall offer all pay channels to its subscribers on a la carte basis and shall specify the maximum retail price for each pay channel\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/dth-players-told-to-offer-pay-channels-on-la-carte-basis/article999298.ece?ref=archive|title=DTH players told to offer pay channels on la carte basis|date=July 23, 2010|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref> Tata Sky, Airtel digital TV, Videocon d2h, and Reliance Digital TV launched A la carte options in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan119.php|title=Now Airtel Digital TV announces a la carte pricing|date=January 18, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan161.php|title=Videocon d2h offers channels a la carte|date=January 22, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan54.php|title=Tata Sky allows subscribers to make their own packs|date=January 10, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan171.php|title=Reliance Digital TV unveils a la carte menu|date=January 24, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019s ===\nThe price of [[Set-top box|set top boxes]] (STB) in India has plummeted in the decade since DTH services were launched. A standard STB was priced at {{INR}}3999 in 2003, but dropped to {{Indian Rupee}}500 by 2014. In the same year, a [[Digital video recorder|DVR]] box capable of recording television programmes was priced at {{INR}}2500.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn September 2012, the Union Government raised the FDI cap in the DTH sector from 49% to 74%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianama.com/2012/09/223-indian-approves-74-fdi-in-dth-mobile-tv-other-broadcasting-services/|title=India Approves 74% FDI In DTH, Mobile TV & Other Broadcasting Services|last=Chaudhary|first=Apurva|date=2012-09-14|website=MediaNama|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> The government permitted 100% FDI in the DTH industry in November 2015, with 49% through the automatic route and higher investments subject to government approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianama.com/2015/11/223-government-fdi-norms-eased/|title=Govt eases FDI norms in broadcasting and 14 other sectors|last=KJ|first=Shashidhar|date=2015-11-10|website=MediaNama|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n\nVideocon d2h began offering a preview of [[4K resolution|4K]] [[4K resolution#Ultra HD|Ultra HD]] content on its DTH service in July 2014, and launched India's first 4K Ultra HD channel on 26 January 2015. The channel is not dedicated to single genre and instead broadcasts [[video on demand]] (VOD), lifestyle and travel content, sports, [[infotainment]], concerts and [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood films]]. The channel also telecasts 4K content created by international broadcasters. The first programs telecast on the channel were live broadcasts of select matches from the [[2015 Cricket World Cup|2015 ICC Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/dth/dth-services/videocon-d2h-rolls-out-india-s-first-4k-ultra-hd-channel-150203|title=Videocon d2h rolls out India\u2019s first 4K Ultra HD channel|date=2015-02-03|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.videocond2h.com/wsc/first_4k_channel.aspx|title=DTH - direct to Home - Videocon d2h satellite TV - DTH Services by Videocon d2h|website=www.videocond2h.com|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> Tata Sky also offered live broadcasts of select matches in 4K.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/tv/features/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-hd-4k-and-the-future-of-television-broadcasts-673616|title=With 4K TV Broadcasts Coming to India, Is It Time for You to Invest in a 4K TV?|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\nReliance Big TV was sold to Pantel Technologies and Veecon Media and Television in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.televisionpost.com/dth-operator-independent-tvs-fy18-net-loss-swells-to-rs-119-3-cr/|title=DTH operator Independent TV\u2019s FY18 net loss swells to Rs 119.3 cr|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> It was rebranded and relaunched as Independent TV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.televisionpost.com/independent-tv-secures-content-deals-with-broadcasters/|title=Independent TV secures content deals with broadcasters|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> On 22 March 2018, [[Dish TV]] merged with [[Videocon d2h]], creating the largest DTH provider in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/media/dish-tv-india-videocon-d2h-merger-completed/articleshow/63414778.cms|title=Dish TV India, Videocon d2h merger completed|date=22 March 2018|website=The Economic Times|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== List of DTH Providers ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!S. No.\n! Service Provider \n!Launch date\n!Subscribers\n<small>June 2019</small><ref name=\"TRAIpir\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/64022878.cms|title=Dish TV plans to continue with Videocon D2H brand - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n!Ownership\n|-\n|1||\n[[DD Free Dish]]\n|December 2004\n|35.0 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/dd-freedishs-free-service-a-concern-for-broadcasters/articleshow/65894146.cms|title=DD FreeDish\u2019s free service a concern for broadcasters|last=Laghate|first=Gaurav|date=2018-09-21|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n|[[Prasar Bharati]]\n|-\n|-\n|2||\n[[Dish TV]]\n|October 2003\n|29.0 million\n|[[Zee Entertainment Enterprises]]\n|-\n|3\n|[[Tata Sky]]\n|August 2006\n|17.39 million\n|[[Tata Sons]] (60%)<br />[[21st Century Fox|The Walt Disney Company]] (through the acquisition of [[21st Century Fox]] assets) (30%)<br />[[Temasek Holdings]] (10%)\n|-\n|4\n|[[Airtel digital TV]]\n|October 2008\n|12.50 million\n|[[Bharti Airtel|Bharti Airtel Limited]] (80%)\n[[Warburg Pincus]] (20%)\n|-\n|5\n| [[Sun Direct]]\n|December 2007\n|7.61 million\n|[[Sun Network]] (80%)<br />[[Astro (satellite TV)|Astro Group]] (20%)\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Satellites==\n{{update section|date=September 2018}}\nThe [[Department of Space]] (DoS) requires all DTH operators in India to only use satellites commissioned by the [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] ([[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]). DTH operators may use capacity leased by ISRO from foreign satellites only if sufficient capacity is not available on ISRO satellites.<ref name=\"TT1\"/> The following 8 satellites are currently in use by Indian DTH service providers:<ref name=\"TT1\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Satellite\n!Owner\n!Launch date\n!Mission life\n!User(s)\n|-\n|[[INSAT-4A]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|12 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[GSAT-10]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[ST-2]]\n|[[Singtel]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[MEASAT-3]]\n|[[MEASAT Satellite Systems]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[GSAT-15]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|12 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[NSS-6]]\n|[[SES S.A.]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[AsiaSat 5]]\n|[[AsiaSat]]\n|\n|17 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[GSAT-17]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|}\n\n==Compression standards==\nAll DTH services in India currently use the [[MPEG-4]] standard of [[signal compression]]. [[MPEG-2]] is still used by DishTV, TATA Sky, DD Free Dish. Upgradation is going on to shift from [[MPEG2]] to [[MPEG4]], but to shift completely from MPEG2 to MPEG4, the subscriber have to change his/her STB 1st because MPEG2 STB can not decode MPEG4 video signal. MPEG-2 permitted each transponder to carry approximately 20 [[Standard-definition television|SD]] channels (fewer, in case of [[High-definition television|HD]] channels), while MPEG-4 enables each transponder to carry approximately 50 SD channels (again, fewer in case of HD channels).<ref name=\"TT1\">{{cite web|title=A handy guide to Satellites used for broadcasting DTH signals in India|url=http://telecomtalk.info/a-handy-guide-to-satellites-used-for-broadcasting-dth-signals-in-india/141807/|website=Telecomtalk.info|accessdate=4 September 2016|date=30 August 2015}}</ref> The bandwidth required to carry a single HD channel is approximately equivalent to the bandwidth required to carry 4 SD channels.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Digital television transition in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{MIBI}}\n{{Telecommunication companies of India}}\n\n[[Category:Indian television-related lists|DTH]]\n[[Category:Indian television networks|DTH]]\n[[Category:Direct broadcast satellite services]]\n", "text_old": "[[Direct-to-home|Direct-to-Home]] (DTH) television is a method of receiving [[satellite television]] by means of signals transmitted from [[direct-broadcast satellite]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pattan|first=Bruno|date=31 March 1993|title=Satellite Systems:Principles and Technologies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0GJWEro9ea4C&dq=sun+outage+satellite&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location=Berlin|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|page=|isbn=9780442013578|access-date=29 July 2014}}</ref> The Government of India permitted the reception and distribution of satellite television signals in November 2000. The first DTH service in the country was launched by [[Dish TV]] on 2 October 2003. [[DD Free Dish]], the first free DTH service in India, was launched by public broadcaster [[Doordarshan|Prasar Bharati]] in December 2004.\n\nIndia is the largest DTH market in the world by number of subscribers. As on 30 June 2019, there were 54.36&nbsp;million active pay DTH subscribers in the country.<ref name=\"TRAIpir\">{{cite press release | url=https://main.trai.gov.in/sites/default/files/PIR_01102019_0.pdf | title=The Indian Telecom Services Performance Indicators | publisher=TRAI | date=1 October 2019 | accessdate=4 October 2019 | page=94-95}}</ref> These figures do not include subscribers of free DTH services. \n\nThe Indian market is serviced by 4 paid DTH providers and one free DTH provider.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background ===\nDTH services were first proposed in India in 1996. The proposal was not approved to due to concerns over national security and negative cultural influence. In 1997, the [[Government of India]] banned DTH services when [[Rupert Murdoch]]-owned Indian Sky Broadcasting (ISkyB) was about to launch its DTH services in the country.<ref name=\"Rediff1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2004/mar/23spec.htm|title=What is DTH?|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> After deliberations among groups of ministers, DTH services were permitted by the [[Third Vajpayee ministry|NDA government]] in November 2000. The ministers made four key recommendations to govern DTH services: no single entity, either private or state-owned, should be permitted a [[monopoly]] in DTH services; the [[vertical integration]] of DTH and [[cable television]] services should be monitored in order to prevent the formation of a monopoly in television distribution; the vertical integration of DTH operators and television channels should be avoided in order to ensure fair competition among TV channels.\n\nThe new policy announced in November 2000 required all DTH operators to set up earth stations in India within 12 months of receiving a license. DTH licenses were priced at $2.14 million with a validity of 10 years. The FDI limit in the DTH sector was capped at 49%, and the company operating the services was required to be headed by an Indian citizen.<ref name=\"Rediff1\"/>\n\n=== Early years ===\nThe first DTH service was launched in India on 2 October 2003 by [[Dish TV]] owned by [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises|Zee]]. The company decided not to compete against entrenched cable operators in metros and urban areas, and instead focused on providing services to rural areas and regions not serviced by cable television. Dish TV acquired 350,000 subscribers within 2 years of the launch.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/10-years-of-dth-in-india-the-other-electronics-revolution-114010100022_1.html|title=10 years of DTH in India: The other electronics revolution|last=Gupta|first=Surajeet Das|date=2014-01-01|newspaper=Business Standard India|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> Public broadcaster [[Doordarshan|Prasar Bharati]] launched DD Direct Plus (now [[DD Free Dish]]) in December 2004. The service is free and offers only [[free-to-air]] channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-prasar-bharati-dth-moving-to-pay-mode-1277779|title=Prasar Bharati DTH moving to pay mode? {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=2009-07-28|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> [[Tata Sky]] was incorporated in 2004 as joint venture between the [[Tata Group]] and [[21st Century Fox|Star India's Parent Company]]. Tata Sky launched DTH services in August 2006. Unlike Dish TV, Tata Sky focused on metros and large cities hoping to attract customers away from cable by offering better picture and audio quality and wider selection of channels.<ref name=\":1\" /> Following legal proceedings between [[Star TV (Asian TV networks)|STAR]] and Zee, in 2007, the two companies called a truce and began offering their channels on each other's services. This decision and Dish TV's acquisition of more transponders enabled them to offer 150 channels on their service, more than any other DTH service in India at the time.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSun Direct and Airtel digital TV launched services in 2007 and 2008 respectively. Reliance Big TV (now [[Reliance Digital TV|Independent TV]]) was launched in August 2008.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/money/2009/apr/29big-tv-to-divest-in-dth-arm.htm \"Big TV launched in August 2008\"]. Retrieved 14 April 2010.</ref> The service acquired 1 million subscribers within 90 days of launch, the fastest ramp-up ever achieved by any DTH operator in the world.<ref>[http://www.powerhomebiz.com/News/112008/big-tv-india2.htm \"BIG TV crosses 1 Million Subscriber Mark Within The 90 Days of Launch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429061849/http://www.powerhomebiz.com/News/112008/big-tv-india2.htm |date=2014-04-29 }}. Retrieved 14 April 2010.</ref> [[Videocon d2h]] launched its services in June 2009.\n\nThe total number of DTH subscribers in India rose from 1.5 million in 2005 to 23 million in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/management/kit-the-dth-industry-in-india-110112200007_1.html|title=KIT: The DTH industry in India|last=Advisors|first=Technopak|date=2010-11-22|newspaper=Business Standard India|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> Sun Direct became the first DTH provider to offer [[High-definition television|high-definition]] (HD) channels in early 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/26440_Discovery-launches-Indias-first-high-definition-channel|title=Discovery launches India's first high definition channel|website=www.afaqs.com|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> Tata Sky began offering HD channels later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/56702/tata-sky-launch-hdtv-more.html|title=Tata Sky to launch HDTV, more interactive channels this year|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> Other DTH providers subsequently began carrying HD channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesstoday.in/gadget/living-tech/hd-channels-a-question-of-resolution/story/18596.html|title=HD Channels: A Question of Resolution|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\n====A la carte====\n{{further information|A la carte pay television}}\nOn 3 September 2007, the [[Telecom Regulatory Authority of India]] (TRAI) issued the ''Telecommunication (Broadcasting and Cable Services) Interconnection (Fourth Amendment) Regulation 2007'', which went into law on December 1; the rules require all broadcasters to offer channels on an [[A la carte pay television|a la carte]] basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/sep/sep28.php|title=Broadcasters to give channels a la carte to DTH operators: Trai|date=September 3, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/09/04/stories/2007090461131300.htm|title=Broadcasters must offer all channels|date=September 4, 2007|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> The regulation states, \"All broadcasters will compulsorily offer all their channels on a la carte basis to DTH operators. Additionally, they may also offer bouquets, but they will not compel any DTH operator to include the entire bouquet in any package being offered by DTH operators to their subscribers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200709031641.htm|title=DTH companies can pick channels of choice: TRAI|date=September 3, 2007|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=May 12, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629104908/http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200709031641.htm|archive-date=June 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Prior to the regulation, only customers in areas covered by the [[conditional access]] system (CAS), and cable systems providing the services, had the option of choosing to buy only the channels they were interested in. TRAI intervened after DTH operators complained that broadcasters were forcing them to carry channels that they did not want.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/6kzrHbFbry3ztsQ5uhVaeK/Trai-unbundles-TV-channels-for-DTH.html|title=Trai unbundles TV channels for DTH|author=Sreejiraj Eluvangal|date=September 4, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=Livemint}}</ref>\n\nSeveral broadcasters, such as [[STAR India]], [[Zee Turner Limited|Zee Turner]], [[Sony Entertainment Television (India)|Set Discovery]] and [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]], challenged TRAI's order in the [[Telecom Disputes Settlement Appellate Tribunal]] (TDSAT).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/nov/nov231.php|title=Zee joins Sony to challenge Trai's regulation in non-CAS areas|date=November 21, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k8/jan/jan32.php|title=Sun moves Tdsat against Trai's a la carte pricing for non-CAS areas|date=January 4, 2008|website=IndianTelevision.com|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/nov/nov246.php|title=A la carte Tariff Order valid from 1 Dec, Tdsat refuses stay|date=November 22, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref> On 15 January 2008, TDSAT refused to grant a stay on the appeal challenging TRAI's directive; TDSAT overruled the broadcasters' objections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/tdsat-refuses-stay-on-trai-directive-to-broadcasters/261771|title=TDSAT refuses stay on Trai directive to broadcasters|date=January 15, 2008|website=Financial Express|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> The agency later set aside TRAI's December 2007 tariff regime. TRAI challenged TDSAT's order in the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]], and stated in proceedings on 22 July 2010 that \"in the [[Analog television|analog]], [[Cable converter box#Addressable cable box|non-addressable]] environment, the authority is of the view that a la carte should not be made mandatory at the wholesale level as technological constraints in any case make it impossible for the benefits of a la carte provisioning to be passed on to subscribers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-07-22/news/27594209_1_la-carte-telecom-regulatory-authority-trai|title=Trai wants to cap cable rate at Rs 250/month|author=Sanjay K Singh|date=July 22, 2010|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=India Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/trai-seeks-sc-nod-to-notify-tariff-order/742347/|title=TRAI seeks SC nod to notify tariff order|date=January 26, 2011|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTRAI ordered that pay television customers in India must be given a free choice of channels rather than be forced to choose package deals, enforcing a January 2011 deadline to implement the changes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/article528738.ece|title=A la carte menu for DTH subscribers at Rs. 150|date=July 22, 2010|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-07-23/news/27614290_1_tariff-order-dth-providers-broadcasters|title=Pick and pay DTH channels from September|date=July 23, 2010|newspaper=India Times|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> The order stated, \"Every service provider providing broadcasting services or cable services to its subscribers using an [[Addressability|addressable system]] shall offer all pay channels to its subscribers on a la carte basis and shall specify the maximum retail price for each pay channel\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/dth-players-told-to-offer-pay-channels-on-la-carte-basis/article999298.ece?ref=archive|title=DTH players told to offer pay channels on la carte basis|date=July 23, 2010|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref> Tata Sky, Airtel digital TV, Videocon d2h, and Reliance Digital TV launched A la carte options in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan119.php|title=Now Airtel Digital TV announces a la carte pricing|date=January 18, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan161.php|title=Videocon d2h offers channels a la carte|date=January 22, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan54.php|title=Tata Sky allows subscribers to make their own packs|date=January 10, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k11/jan/jan171.php|title=Reliance Digital TV unveils a la carte menu|date=January 24, 2011|accessdate=May 12, 2013|website=IndianTelevision.com}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019s ===\nThe price of [[Set-top box|set top boxes]] (STB) in India has plummeted in the decade since DTH services were launched. A standard STB was priced at {{INR}}3999 in 2003, but dropped to {{Indian Rupee}}500 by 2014. In the same year, a [[Digital video recorder|DVR]] box capable of recording television programmes was priced at {{INR}}2500.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn September 2012, the Union Government raised the FDI cap in the DTH sector from 49% to 74%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianama.com/2012/09/223-indian-approves-74-fdi-in-dth-mobile-tv-other-broadcasting-services/|title=India Approves 74% FDI In DTH, Mobile TV & Other Broadcasting Services|last=Chaudhary|first=Apurva|date=2012-09-14|website=MediaNama|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref> The government permitted 100% FDI in the DTH industry in November 2015, with 49% through the automatic route and higher investments subject to government approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medianama.com/2015/11/223-government-fdi-norms-eased/|title=Govt eases FDI norms in broadcasting and 14 other sectors|last=KJ|first=Shashidhar|date=2015-11-10|website=MediaNama|access-date=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n\nVideocon d2h began offering a preview of [[4K resolution|4K]] [[4K resolution#Ultra HD|Ultra HD]] content on its DTH service in July 2014, and launched India's first 4K Ultra HD channel on 26 January 2015. The channel is not dedicated to single genre and instead broadcasts [[video on demand]] (VOD), lifestyle and travel content, sports, [[infotainment]], concerts and [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood films]]. The channel also telecasts 4K content created by international broadcasters. The first programs telecast on the channel were live broadcasts of select matches from the [[2015 Cricket World Cup|2015 ICC Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/dth/dth-services/videocon-d2h-rolls-out-india-s-first-4k-ultra-hd-channel-150203|title=Videocon d2h rolls out India\u2019s first 4K Ultra HD channel|date=2015-02-03|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.videocond2h.com/wsc/first_4k_channel.aspx|title=DTH - direct to Home - Videocon d2h satellite TV - DTH Services by Videocon d2h|website=www.videocond2h.com|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> Tata Sky also offered live broadcasts of select matches in 4K.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/tv/features/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-hd-4k-and-the-future-of-television-broadcasts-673616|title=With 4K TV Broadcasts Coming to India, Is It Time for You to Invest in a 4K TV?|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\nReliance Big TV was sold to Pantel Technologies and Veecon Media and Television in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.televisionpost.com/dth-operator-independent-tvs-fy18-net-loss-swells-to-rs-119-3-cr/|title=DTH operator Independent TV\u2019s FY18 net loss swells to Rs 119.3 cr|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> It was rebranded and relaunched as Independent TV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.televisionpost.com/independent-tv-secures-content-deals-with-broadcasters/|title=Independent TV secures content deals with broadcasters|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> On 22 March 2018, [[Dish TV]] merged with [[Videocon d2h]], creating the largest DTH provider in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/media/dish-tv-india-videocon-d2h-merger-completed/articleshow/63414778.cms|title=Dish TV India, Videocon d2h merger completed|date=22 March 2018|website=The Economic Times|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== List of DTH Providers ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!S. No.\n! Service Provider \n!Launch date\n!Subscribers\n<small>June 2019</small><ref name=\"TRAIpir\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/64022878.cms|title=Dish TV plans to continue with Videocon D2H brand - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n!Ownership\n|-\n|1||\n[[DD Free Dish]]\n|December 2004\n|35.0 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/dd-freedishs-free-service-a-concern-for-broadcasters/articleshow/65894146.cms|title=DD FreeDish\u2019s free service a concern for broadcasters|last=Laghate|first=Gaurav|date=2018-09-21|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n|[[Prasar Bharati]]\n|-\n|-\n|2||\n[[Dish TV]]\n|October 2003\n|29.0 million\n|[[Zee Entertainment Enterprises]]\n|-\n|3\n|[[Tata Sky]]\n|August 2006\n|17.39 million\n|[[Tata Sons]] (60%)<br />[[21st Century Fox|The Walt Disney Company]] (through the acquisition of [[21st Century Fox]] assets) (30%)<br />[[Temasek Holdings]] (10%)\n|-\n|4\n|[[Airtel digital TV]]\n|October 2008\n|12.50 million\n|[[Bharti Airtel|Bharti Airtel Limited]] (80%)\n[[Warburg Pincus]] (20%)\n|-\n|5\n| [[Sun Direct]]\n|December 2007\n|7.61 million\n|[[Sun Network]] (80%)<br />[[Astro (satellite TV)|Astro Group]] (20%)\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Satellites==\n{{update section|date=September 2018}}\nThe [[Department of Space]] (DoS) requires all DTH operators in India to only use satellites commissioned by the [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] ([[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]). DTH operators may use capacity leased by ISRO from foreign satellites only if sufficient capacity is not available on ISRO satellites.<ref name=\"TT1\"/> The following 8 satellites are currently in use by Indian DTH service providers:<ref name=\"TT1\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Satellite\n!Owner\n!Launch date\n!Mission life\n!User(s)\n|-\n|[[INSAT-4A]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|12 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[GSAT-10]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[ST-2]]\n|[[Singtel]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[MEASAT-3]]\n|[[MEASAT Satellite Systems]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[GSAT-15]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|12 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[NSS-6]]\n|[[SES S.A.]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[AsiaSat 5]]\n|[[AsiaSat]]\n|\n|17 years\n|Freeview\n|-\n|[[GSAT-17]]\n|[[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n|\n|15 years\n|Freeview\n|}\n\n==Compression standards==\nAll DTH services in India currently use the [[MPEG-4]] standard of [[signal compression]]. [[MPEG-2]] is still used by DishTV, TATA Sky, DD Free Dish. Upgradation is going on to shift from [[MPEG2]] to [[MPEG4]], but to shift completely from MPEG2 to MPEG4, the subscriber have to change his/her STB 1st because MPEG2 STB can not decode MPEG4 video signal. MPEG-2 permitted each transponder to carry approximately 20 [[Standard-definition television|SD]] channels (fewer, in case of [[High-definition television|HD]] channels), while MPEG-4 enables each transponder to carry approximately 50 SD channels (again, fewer in case of HD channels).<ref name=\"TT1\">{{cite web|title=A handy guide to Satellites used for broadcasting DTH signals in India|url=http://telecomtalk.info/a-handy-guide-to-satellites-used-for-broadcasting-dth-signals-in-india/141807/|website=Telecomtalk.info|accessdate=4 September 2016|date=30 August 2015}}</ref> The bandwidth required to carry a single HD channel is approximately equivalent to the bandwidth required to carry 4 SD channels.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Digital television transition in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{MIBI}}\n{{Telecommunication companies of India}}\n\n[[Category:Indian television-related lists|DTH]]\n[[Category:Indian television networks|DTH]]\n[[Category:Direct broadcast satellite services]]\n", "name_user": "Subhamsatapathy013", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList of DTH Providers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direct-to-home_television_in_India"}
{"title_page": "New Jersey Hall of Fame", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\nThe '''New Jersey Hall of Fame''' is an organization that honors individuals from the U.S. state of [[New Jersey]] who have made contributions to society and the world beyond.\n\nThe [[Hall of Fame]] is a designated 501(c)(3) non-profit organization, overseen by a Board of Trustees. It was statutorily authorized through Public Law 2005, Chapter 232.<ref>{{cite web | title=Will Sports and Exposition Authority get out of Hall of Fame business? | website=North Jersey | date=January 20, 2017 | url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2017/01/20/sports-and-exposition-authority-get-out-hall-fame-business/96733316/ | access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> This bi-partisan legislation was passed unanimously in the [[New Jersey Senate]] on May 13, 2005,<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9404EFDA1130F930A25756C0A9639C8B63 \"Metro Briefing |New Jersey: Trenton: Lawmakers Push Hall Of Fame\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 13, 2005. Accessed December 29, 2007.</ref> passed in the Assembly on June 30, 2005, and signed into law by the governor on September 22, 2005.<ref name=\"FactSheet\">[http://www.njhalloffame.com/factsheet.htm New Jersey Hall of Fame Fact Sheet]. NJHoF website. Retrieved 2010-08-21.</ref> \n\nIn June 2013 it introduced a \"mobile museum\" designed by Michael Graves and Ralph Applebaum<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globenewswire.com/news-release/2016/06/21/850299/0/en/Renovated-New-Jersey-Hall-of-Fame-Mobile-Museum-Debuts-at-NJ-State-Fair.html|title=Renovated New Jersey Hall of Fame Mobile Museum Debuts at NJ State Fair|last=|first=|date=2016-06-21|work=GlobeNewswire News Room|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref> which toured the state for more than 300,000 people over three years.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/06/nj_hall_of_fame_inducts_16_unveils_500k_mobile_museum.html#/0 N.J. Hall of Fame inducts 16, unveils $500K mobile museum]. NJ.com (2013-06-24). Retrieved on 2013-10-23.</ref><ref>[http://www.northjersey.com/news/212868691_Newest_NJ_Hall_of_Fame_members_announced_and_new_mobile_museum_launched.html Newest NJ Hall of Fame members announced and new mobile museum launched]. NorthJersey.com (2013-06-25). Retrieved on 2013-10-23.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/passaic-county/index.ssf/2017/02/the_nj_hall_of_fame_lives_in_a_trailer_and_one_city_wants_to_change_that.html|title=The N.J. Hall of Fame lives in a trailer and one city wants to change that|author=|date=February 2017|website=NJ.com|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, it opened a satellite exhibition of five holograms, posters and a \u2033Wall of Fame\u2033  at [[Newark Airport]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metroairportnews.com/new-jersey-hall-of-fame-exhibition-coming-to-newark-airport/|title=New Jersey Hall of Fame Exhibition Coming to Newark Airport - Metropolitan Airport News|date=2017-12-21|work=Metropolitan Airport News|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref> In September 2018 it was announced that the Hall of Fame would move to a permanent home at [[American Dream Meadowlands]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2018/09/nj_hall_of_fame_lands_a_home_at_the_american_dream_megamall_no_really.html|title=N.J. Hall of Fame lands a home at the American Dream megamall. No, really|work=NJ.com|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe New Jersey Hall of Fame selects potential nominees in five categories: General, Enterprise, Sports, Arts & Entertainment, and Historical. With only rare exceptions, nominees must have resided in New Jersey for a period of at least five years. Selection of inductees is done using a three-phase process. Phase I is conducted by a group of expert panelists selected by the New Jersey Hall of Fame Board, who compose a list of 20 individuals in each category. Phase II incorporates a group of over 100 prominent organization throughout New Jersey who narrow the field down to 6 individuals in each category. Phase III uses a public voting system via the internet and manual ballots. Upon completion of Phase III, the New Jersey Hall of Fame Board selects its inductees based on the top vote-getter in each category, as well as others the board deems deserving.<ref name=FactSheet/>\n\n==Induction ceremony==\nThe first class of inductees was honored in an induction ceremony at the [[New Jersey Performing Arts Center]] on May 4, 2008.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2008/05/new_jersey_hall_of_fame_welcom.html New Jersey Hall of Fame welcomes first-ever class], ''The Star-Ledger'', May 4, 2008. Retrieved May 3, 2010.</ref>\n\n==2008 inductees==\nThe inaugural class of inductees for the New Jersey Hall of Fame were announced in a press conference on October 25, 2007, by Governor [[Jon Corzine]].<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2007/10/frank_bruce_and_buzz_among_fir.html Frank, Bruce and Buzz among first inducted into NJ hall of fame], ''The Star-Ledger'', October 25, 2007. Retrieved May 3, 2010.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Historical\n! Enterprise\n! Arts & Entertainment\n! Sports\n! General\n|-\n|\n* [[Clara Barton]]\n* [[Thomas Edison]]\n* [[Albert Einstein]]\n|\n* [[Buzz Aldrin]]\n* [[Malcolm Forbes]]\n* [[Robert Wood Johnson II]]\n|\n* [[Frank Sinatra]]\n* [[Bruce Springsteen]]\n* [[Meryl Streep]]\n|\n* [[Yogi Berra]]\n* [[Bill Bradley]]\n* [[Vince Lombardi]]\n|\n* [[Toni Morrison]]\n* [[Norman Schwarzkopf]]\n* [[Harriet Tubman]]\n|}\n\n==2009 inductees==\nThe 2009 class of inductees for the New Jersey Hall of Fame were announced on February 2, 2009.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2009/02/bon_jovi_shaq_abbott_and_coste.html Bon Jovi, Shaq, Abbott and Costello make N.J. Hall of Fame], ''The Star-Ledger'', February 2, 2009. Retrieved May 3, 2010.</ref> The induction ceremony was held May 3, 2009, at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2009/05/2009_new_jersey_hall_of_fame_i.html 2009 New Jersey Hall of Fame inductees welcomed at NJPAC]. ''The Star-Ledger'', May 3, 2009. Retrieved May 3, 2010.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Historical\n! Enterprise\n! Arts & Entertainment\n! Sports\n! General\n|-\n|\n* [[Paul Robeson]]\n* [[Walt Whitman]]\n|\n* [[Guglielmo Marconi]]\n* [[Carl Sagan]]\n|\n* [[Bud Abbott]] & [[Lou Costello]]\n* [[Jon Bon Jovi]]\n* [[Jerry Lewis]]\n|\n* [[Althea Gibson]]\n* [[Shaquille O'Neal]]\n* [[Phil Rizzuto]]\n|\n* [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]]\n* [[William Carlos Williams]]\n|}\n\n==2010 inductees==\nThe 2010 class of inductees for the New Jersey Hall of Fame were announced on December 3, 2009.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2009/12/new_jersey_hall_of_fame_announ.html Count Basie, Jack Nicholson, Les Paul make New Jersey Hall of Fame], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', December 3, 2009. Retrieved May 3, 2010.</ref> The induction ceremony was held May 2, 2010, at the [[New Jersey Performing Arts Center]] in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]].<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/05/jack_nicholson_susan_sarandon.html Jack Nicholson, Susan Sarandon are among 15 inducted into N.J. Hall of Fame], ''The Star-Ledger'', May 2, 2010. Retrieved May 3, 2010.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Historical\n! Enterprise\n! Arts & Entertainment\n! Sports\n! General\n|-\n|\n* [[Alice Paul]]\n* [[Les Paul]]\n* [[Woodrow Wilson]]\n|\n* [[Michael Graves]]\n* [[Wally Schirra]]\n|\n* [[Count Basie]]\n* [[Danny DeVito]]\n* [[Jack Nicholson]]\n* [[Susan Sarandon]]\n* [[Frankie Valli]]\n|\n* [[Larry Doby]]\n* [[Carl Lewis]]\n|\n* [[Judy Blume]]\n* [[William J. Brennan, Jr.|William Brennan]]\n* [[Philip Roth]]\n|}\n\n==2011 inductees==\n:''For list of inductees, see footnote''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://njhalloffame.org/hall-of-famers/2011-inductees|title=New Jersey Hall of Fame - 2011 Inductees|publisher=New Jersey Hall of Fame|date=|access-date=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Historical\n! Enterprise\n! Arts & Entertainment\n! Sports\n! General\n|-\n|\n* [[John Basilone]]\n|\n* [[Leon Hess]]\n|\n* [[Tony Bennett]]\n* [[Queen Latifah]]\n* [[Bucky Pizzarelli|John \"Bucky\" Pizzarelli]]\n* [[John Travolta]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n|\n* [[Franco Harris]]\n* [[Joe Theismann]]\n|\n* [[Brendan Byrne]]\n* [[Mary Higgins Clark]]\n* [[William Halsey Jr.|William \"Bull\" Halsey]]\n|}\nThe [[9/11 Victims]] were also given a special induction.\n\n==2012 inductees==\n:''For list of inductees, see footnote''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://njhalloffame.org/hall-of-famers/2012-inductees |title=New Jersey Hall of Fame - 2012 Inductees |publisher=New Jersey Hall of Fame |date=|accessdate=2017-07-21}}</ref>\nTen members of the Class of 2012 were inducted on Saturday, June 9, 2012, during a ceremony at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center: [[Milt Campbell]] (Olympian), [[John Dorrance]] (condensed-soup inventor), [[Michael Douglas]] (actor), [[Bob Hurley]] (basketball coach), [[Wellington Mara]] (New York Giants owner), [[Samuel Irving Newhouse, Sr.|Samuel I. Newhouse]] (media mogul), [[Annie Oakley]] (Wild West Show sensation), [[Joyce Carol Oates]] (author), [[Christopher Reeve]] (late actor-activist), and [[Sarah Vaughan]] (jazz singer).<ref name=AndrewDuffelmeyer>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Duffelmeyer |title=New Jersey Hall of Fame welcomes 10 new members |date=June 9, 2012 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[The Press of Atlantic City]] |url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/breaking/new-jersey-hall-of-fame-welcomes-new-members/article_18cfd3f2-b301-11e1-b042-001a4bcf887a.html |accessdate=2017-07-21}}</ref>\n\nThe eleventh member of the Class of 2012&nbsp;\u2013 the [[E Street Band]]&nbsp;\u2013 will be inducted at a future date.<ref name=AndrewDuffelmeyer/> The Unsung Hero Award was given to [[Eric LeGrand]], the paralyzed former Rutgers University defensive tackle.<ref name=AndrewDuffelmeyer/>\n\